Human: Write a C++ program to generate a list of prime numbers between 1 and 1000. The program should include a function to check if a number is prime and another function to generate the list of prime numbers. The program should also include error handling to manage cases where the input number is not a prime number. Additionally, the program should be able to handle large input numbers efficiently without causing a time or space complexity issue. Provide a brief explanation of how the program works.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <cmath>
#include <cassert>

// Function to check if a number is prime
bool isPrime(int number) {
    if (number <= 1) return false;
    for (int i = 2; i <= sqrt(number); i++) {
        if (number % i == 0) return false;
    }
    return true;
}

// Function to generate a list of prime numbers between 1 and 1000
std::vector<int> generatePrimes(int start, int end) {
    std::vector<int> primes;
    for (int num = start; num <= end; num++) {
        if (isPrime(num)) {
            primes.push_back(num);
        }
    }
    return primes;
}

int main() {
    try {
        // Test the generatePrimes function with a range of numbers
        std::vector<int> primes = generatePrimes(1, 1000);
        for (int prime : primes) {
            std::cout << prime << " ";
        }
        std::cout << std::endl;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Error: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```
